There are three main types: GPS, A-GPS and GLONASS. GPS - This is one of the most widespread global positioning technologies, developed and maintained by the U.S. government. It uses satellites in order to detect your location. Works best in clear weather. A-GPS - A-GPS stands for Assisted GPS and is the industry standard for positioning and navigation. ‰ÛÏAssisted‰Ûù means that it can use local wireless networks, in addition to satellites, for quicker and more precise localization. GLONASS - GLONASS is a global positioning system, developed by the Russian Federation. It‰Ûªs very similar to GPS, but isn‰Ûªt so popular in cell phones. VX7000A				http://www.phonearena.com/phones/LG-VX7000--VX7000A_id710	19-Dec-03	" 1000 mAh Technology CDMA: CDMA - Code Division Multiple Access. A technique of multiplexing, also called spread spectrum, in which analog signals are converted into digital form for transmission. For each communication channel, the signals are encoded in a sequence known to the transmitter and the receiver for that channel. The foremost application is digital cellular phone technology from QUALCOMM that operates in the 800MHz band and 1.9GHz PCS band. CDMA phones are noted for their excellent call quality and long battery life. 800, 1900 MHz AMPS: AMPS - Advanced mobile phone standard. Analogue standard used widely in North America. 800 MHz Positioning: Positioning - This field shows the positioning systems supported by the device. There are three main types: GPS, A-GPS and GLONASS. GPS - This is one of the most widespread global positioning technologies, developed and maintained by the U.S. government. It uses satellites in order to detect your location. Works best in clear weather. A-GPS - A-GPS stands for Assisted GPS and is the industry standard for positioning and navigation. ‰ÛÏAssisted‰Ûù means that it can use local wireless networks, in addition to satellites, for quicker and more precise localization. GLONASS - GLONASS is a global positioning system, developed by the Russian Federation. It‰Ûªs very similar to GPS, but isn‰Ûªt so popular in cell phones. System chip: System chip - Most modern handsets use an advanced chip that includes many of the device‰Ûªs hardware modules like the processor, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth and sometimes even the wireless radio. Some more powerful smartphones use dual-core and quad-core processors designed to deliver greater performance. Dual-core, 1500 MHz, Krait Graphics processor: Adreno 225 System memory: System memory - System memory, or RAM memory is the type of memory that the device uses to temporarily store data from the OS or currently-running apps. The more RAM available to the device, the better the performance will be when multiple or heavier programs are running. 2048 MB RAM Built-in storage: 16 GB Storage expansion: microSD, microSDHC up to 32 GB Battery Talk time: 13.00 hours the average is 15 h (884 min) Stand-by time: 15.3 days (367 hours) the average is 18 days (425 h) Talk time (3G): 13.50 hours the average is 15 h (913 min) Stand-by time (3G): 14.8 days (355 hours) the average is 24 days (580 h) Music playback: 61.00 hours Video playback: 9.00 hours Capacity: 2100 mAh Multimedia Music player: Filter by: Album, Artist, Playlists Features: Album art cover, Background playback Radio: FM Speakers: Earpiece, Loudspeaker Technology CDMA: CDMA - Code Division Multiple Access. A technique of multiplexing, also called spread spectrum, in which analog signals are converted into digital form for transmission. For each communication channel, the signals are encoded in a sequence known to the transmitter and the receiver for that channel. The foremost application is digital cellular phone technology from QUALCOMM that operates in the 800MHz band and 1.9GHz PCS band. CDMA phones are noted for their excellent call quality and long battery life. 800, 1900 MHz GSM: 850, 900, 1800, 1900 MHz UMTS: 850, 1700/2100, 1900, 2100 MHz FDD LTE: 700 (band 13), 700 (band 17), 850 (band 5), 1700/2100 (band 4), 1900 (band 2) MHz Data: LTE, HSPA (unspecified), UMTS, EDGE, GPRS Positioning: Positioning - This field shows the positioning systems supported by the device. There are three main types: GPS, A-GPS and GLONASS. GPS - This is one of the most widespread global positioning technologies, developed and maintained by the U.S. government. It uses satellites in order to detect your location. Works best in clear weather. A-GPS - A-GPS stands for Assisted GPS and is the industry standard for positioning and navigation. ‰ÛÏAssisted‰Ûù means that it can use local wireless networks, in addition to satellites, for quicker and more precise localization. GLONASS - GLONASS is a global positioning system, developed by the Russian Federation. It‰Ûªs very similar to GPS, but isn‰Ûªt so popular in cell phones. SGH-S307				http://www.phonearena.com/phones/Samsung-SGH-S307_id541	12-Mar-03	" 1000 mAh specifications continue after the ad Technology CDMA: CDMA - Code Division Multiple Access. A technique of multiplexing, also called spread spectrum, in which analog signals are converted into digital form for transmission. For each communication channel, the signals are encoded in a sequence known to the transmitter and the receiver for that channel. The foremost application is digital cellular phone technology from QUALCOMM that operates in the 800MHz band and 1.9GHz PCS band. CDMA phones are noted for their excellent call quality and long battery life. 800, 1900 MHz AMPS: AMPS - Advanced mobile phone standard. Analogue standard used widely in North America. 800 MHz Positioning: Positioning - This field shows the positioning systems supported by the device. There are three main types: GPS, A-GPS and GLONASS. GPS - This is one of the most widespread global positioning technologies, developed and maintained by the U.S. government. It uses satellites in order to detect your location. Works best in clear weather. A-GPS - A-GPS stands for Assisted GPS and is the industry standard for positioning and navigation. ‰ÛÏAssisted‰Ûù means that it can use local wireless networks, in addition to satellites, for quicker and more precise localization. GLONASS - GLONASS is a global positioning system, developed by the Russian Federation. It‰Ûªs very similar to GPS, but isn‰Ûªt so popular in cell phones. Some more powerful smartphones use dual-core and quad-core processors designed to deliver greater performance. Single core, 460 MHz, K3 Hi3611 System memory: System memory - System memory, or RAM memory is the type of memory that the device uses to temporarily store data from the OS or currently-running apps. The more RAM available to the device, the better the performance will be when multiple or heavier programs are running. 128 MB RAM / 256 MB ROM Storage expansion: microSD, microSDHC Battery Talk time: 5.00 hours the average is 14 h (828 min) Stand-by time: 20.0 days (480 hours) the average is 17 days (417 h) Capacity: 1500 mAh Multimedia Speakers: Earpiece, Loudspeaker Technology GSM: 850, 900, 1800, 1900 MHz Data: GPRS Positioning: Positioning - This field shows the positioning systems supported by the device. There are three main types: GPS, A-GPS and GLONASS. GPS - This is one of the most widespread global positioning technologies, developed and maintained by the U.S. government. It uses satellites in order to detect your location. Works best in clear weather. A-GPS - A-GPS stands for Assisted GPS and is the industry standard for positioning and navigation. ‰ÛÏAssisted‰Ûù means that it can use local wireless networks, in addition to satellites, for quicker and more precise localization. GLONASS - GLONASS is a global positioning system, developed by the Russian Federation. It‰Ûªs very similar to GPS, but isn‰Ûªt so popular in cell phones. The more RAM available to the device, the better the performance will be when multiple or heavier programs are running. 1000 MB RAM Built-in storage: 8 GB Storage expansion: microSD, microSDHC Battery Not user replaceable: Yes Multimedia Music player: Filter by: Album, Artist, Playlists Features: Album art cover, Background playback Speakers: Stereo speakers Internet browsing Built-in online services support: YouTube (upload), Picasa/Google+ Technology Positioning: Positioning - This field shows the positioning systems supported by the device. There are three main types: GPS, A-GPS and GLONASS. GPS - This is one of the most widespread global positioning technologies, developed and maintained by the U.S. government. It uses satellites in order to detect your location. Works best in clear weather. A-GPS - A-GPS stands for Assisted GPS and is the industry standard for positioning and navigation. ‰ÛÏAssisted‰Ûù means that it can use local wireless networks, in addition to satellites, for quicker and more precise localization. GLONASS - GLONASS is a global positioning system, developed by the Russian Federation. It‰Ûªs very similar to GPS, but isn‰Ûªt so popular in cell phones. Features: Light sensor Hardware Processor: Processor - The processor is the main computing component of a phone and is a major factor when it comes to the overall speed of the device. Some more powerful smartphones use dual-core and quad-core processors designed to deliver greater performance. There are three main types: GPS, A-GPS and GLONASS. GPS - This is one of the most widespread global positioning technologies, developed and maintained by the U.S. government. It uses satellites in order to detect your location. Works best in clear weather. A-GPS - A-GPS stands for Assisted GPS and is the industry standard for positioning and navigation. ‰ÛÏAssisted‰Ûù means that it can use local wireless networks, in addition to satellites, for quicker and more precise localization. GLONASS - GLONASS is a global positioning system, developed by the Russian Federation. It‰Ûªs very similar to GPS, but isn‰Ûªt so popular in cell phones. K9				http://www.phonearena.com/phones/Kyocera-K9_id926	100 g8-Dec-04	" 900 mAh specifications continue after the ad Technology CDMA: CDMA - Code Division Multiple Access. A technique of multiplexing, also called spread spectrum, in which analog signals are converted into digital form for transmission. For each communication channel, the signals are encoded in a sequence known to the transmitter and the receiver for that channel. The foremost application is digital cellular phone technology from QUALCOMM that operates in the 800MHz band and 1.9GHz PCS band. CDMA phones are noted for their excellent call quality and long battery life. 800, 1900 MHz AMPS: AMPS - Advanced mobile phone standard. Analogue standard used widely in North America. 800 MHz Positioning: Positioning - This field shows the positioning systems supported by the device. There are three main types: GPS, A-GPS and GLONASS. GPS - This is one of the most widespread global positioning technologies, developed and maintained by the U.S. government. It uses satellites in order to detect your location. Works best in clear weather. A-GPS - A-GPS stands for Assisted GPS and is the industry standard for positioning and navigation. ‰ÛÏAssisted‰Ûù means that it can use local wireless networks, in addition to satellites, for quicker and more precise localization. GLONASS - GLONASS is a global positioning system, developed by the Russian Federation. It‰Ûªs very similar to GPS, but isn‰Ûªt so popular in cell phones. There are three main types: GPS, A-GPS and GLONASS. GPS - This is one of the most widespread global positioning technologies, developed and maintained by the U.S. government. It uses satellites in order to detect your location. Works best in clear weather. A-GPS - A-GPS stands for Assisted GPS and is the industry standard for positioning and navigation. ‰ÛÏAssisted‰Ûù means that it can use local wireless networks, in addition to satellites, for quicker and more precise localization. CDM-8945				http://www.phonearena.com/phones/PCD-CDM-8945_id1449	12-Apr-06	" 950 mAh Technology CDMA: CDMA - Code Division Multiple Access. A technique of multiplexing, also called spread spectrum, in which analog signals are converted into digital form for transmission. For each communication channel, the signals are encoded in a sequence known to the transmitter and the receiver for that channel. The foremost application is digital cellular phone technology from QUALCOMM that operates in the 800MHz band and 1.9GHz PCS band. CDMA phones are noted for their excellent call quality and long battery life. 800, 1900 MHz AMPS: AMPS - Advanced mobile phone standard. Analogue standard used widely in North America. 800 MHz Positioning: Positioning - This field shows the positioning systems supported by the device. There are three main types: GPS, A-GPS and GLONASS. GPS - This is one of the most widespread global positioning technologies, developed and maintained by the U.S. government. It uses satellites in order to detect your location. Works best in clear weather. A-GPS - A-GPS stands for Assisted GPS and is the industry standard for positioning and navigation. ‰ÛÏAssisted‰Ûù means that it can use local wireless networks, in addition to satellites, for quicker and more precise localization. GLONASS - GLONASS is a global positioning system, developed by the Russian Federation. It‰Ûªs very similar to GPS, but isn‰Ûªt so popular in cell phones. A technique of multiplexing, also called spread spectrum, in which analog signals are converted into digital form for transmission. The foremost application is digital cellular phone technology from QUALCOMM that operates in the 800MHz band and 1.9GHz PCS band. CDMA: CDMA - Code Division Multiple Access. A technique of multiplexing, also called spread spectrum, in which analog signals are converted into digital form for transmission. For each communication channel, the signals are encoded in a sequence known to the transmitter and the receiver for that channel. The foremost application is digital cellular phone technology from QUALCOMM that operates in the 800MHz band and 1.9GHz PCS band. CDMA phones are noted for their excellent call quality and long battery life. 800, 1700/2100, 1900 MHz Data: EV-DO Positioning: Positioning - This field shows the positioning systems supported by the device. There are three main types: GPS, A-GPS and GLONASS. GPS - This is one of the most widespread global positioning technologies, developed and maintained by the U.S. government. It uses satellites in order to detect your location. Works best in clear weather. A-GPS - A-GPS stands for Assisted GPS and is the industry standard for positioning and navigation. ‰ÛÏAssisted‰Ûù means that it can use local wireless networks, in addition to satellites, for quicker and more precise localization. GLONASS - GLONASS is a global positioning system, developed by the Russian Federation. It‰Ûªs very similar to GPS, but isn‰Ûªt so popular in cell phones. Multi-touch Camera Front-facing camera: Yes Hardware System chip: System chip - Most modern handsets use an advanced chip that includes many of the device‰Ûªs hardware modules like the processor, Wi-Fi, Bluetooth and sometimes even the wireless radio. This field shows what particular system chip (or System-on-a-Chip) is used in the phone. Intel Atom Z2760 Processor: Processor - The processor is the main computing component of a phone and is a major factor when it comes to the overall speed of the device. Some more powerful smartphones use dual-core and quad-core processors designed to deliver greater performance. Dual-core, 1800 MHz, Saltwell Graphics processor: Intel HD Graphics System memory: System memory - System memory, or RAM memory is the type of memory that the device uses to temporarily store data from the OS or currently-running apps. The more RAM available to the device, the better the performance will be when multiple or heavier programs are running. 2048 MB RAM Built-in storage: 64 GB Storage expansion: microSD, microSDHC up to 32 GB Battery Capacity: 6800 mAh Multimedia Music player: Filter by: Album, Artist, Playlists Features: Album art cover, Background playback Speakers: Stereo speakers YouTube player: Yes Internet browsing Built-in online services support: YouTube (upload) Technology Data: HSPA (unspecified), EDGE, GPRS Positioning: Positioning - This field shows the positioning systems supported by the device. There are three main types: GPS, A-GPS and GLONASS. GPS - This is one of the most widespread global positioning technologies, developed and maintained by the U.S. government. It uses satellites in order to detect your location. Works best in clear weather. A-GPS - A-GPS stands for Assisted GPS and is the industry standard for positioning and navigation. ‰ÛÏAssisted‰Ûù means that it can use local wireless networks, in addition to satellites, for quicker and more precise localization. GLONASS - GLONASS is a global positioning system, developed by the Russian Federation. It‰Ûªs very similar to GPS, but isn‰Ûªt so popular in cell phones. A-GPS - A-GPS stands for Assisted GPS and is the industry standard for positioning and navigation. ‰ÛÏAssisted‰Ûù means that it can use local wireless networks, in addition to satellites, for quicker and more precise localization. GLONASS - GLONASS is a global positioning system, developed by the Russian Federation. It‰Ûªs very similar to GPS, but isn‰Ûªt so popular in cell phones.
